{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"f421a88c-74cd-4923-938f-56d1fccc881e","content":"The repository doesn't contain documentation on this topic, but here's the general guidance for macOS:\n\n**Recovering a crash dump on macOS without `createdump`:**\n\n1. **Check for macOS-generated crash reports** — macOS automatically writes crash logs to:\n   - `~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/`\n   - `/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/`\n\n   Look for files matching your process name (`.ips` or `.crash` extension).\n\n2. **Enable core dumps** before reproducing:\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   sudo sysctl kern.corefile=/tmp/core.%P\n   ```\n   Then re-run the app. The core file will be written to `/tmp/`.\n\n3. **Use `lldb` to analyze** the core dump:\n   ```bash\n   lldb --core /tmp/core.<pid> /path/to/your/app\n   ```\n\n4. **If SIP blocks core dumps**, you may need to (temporarily) adjust System Integrity Protection or use `lldb` to attach live:\n   ```bash\n   lldb -- /path/to/your/app [args]\n   ```\n\n5. **For NativeAOT specifically**, since there's no managed `createdump`, the macOS crash report (step 1) plus a core file (step 2) analyzed with `lldb` is the primary workflow. You can load the SOS/dotnet-dump extensions if the runtime symbols are available, but with NativeAOT the native `lldb` backtrace is usually sufficient.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"d7bd8467-fe62-41f5-8296-d19ddf266281","outputTokens":371,"requestId":"784B:A2F50:47A341:535D5D:69FA9E33"},"id":"b1cb25ee-a59d-4d11-a661-21f240127edf","timestamp":"2026-05-06T01:49:50.330Z","parentId":"075b0a7a-b1f2-4f75-9b68-ca22e7a59d1f"}
